  Issues and Suggestions

  1. package in markdown — missing explicit anchor

  The plan says: "In markdown we don't need to add <a id="package-ID"></a>;
  that's done by the markdown processor."

  This is risky. GitHub Markdown generates anchors by lowercasing and stripping
  special characters, so ### Package Foo.Bar would become #package-foobar (dot
  stripped), not #package-foo.bar. Since LTAC IDs can contain dots and other
  non-alphanumeric chars, links to #package-ID from pkg_cited/pkg_citing would
  break. The element selector rightly generates an explicit <a> — package should
   too, for consistency and correctness.

  2. HTML <h3 id="..."> includes the statement

  The draft shows:
  <h3 id="ELEMENT_TYPE-ID-ELEMENT_STATEMENT">
  Including the full statement in the id is problematic — statements contain
  spaces, colons, and other characters that make fragment IDs unreliable. The <a
   id="..."> is already doing the anchor job. The <h3> probably shouldn't have
  its own id, or if it does, it should just be ELEMENT_TYPE-ID.

  3. referenced_by semantics need precision

  "hyperlinked list of packages containing it, starting with the one it's
  defined in" — does "containing it" mean packages that cite it, or packages
  where it appears (defined or cited)? An element is only defined in one
  package, but it could be cited in many. Be explicit: "the package that defines
   it, followed by all packages that cite it, in LTAC file order."

  4. supports semantics need precision

  "hyperlinked list of parents of the definition and all citations" — unclear.
  Does this mean: all elements for which this element is a structural child? Say
   so directly: "all elements in any package that have this element as a direct
  structural child (i.e., this element's parent(s) in the argument tree)."

  5. config directive — behavior questions

  <!-- caseproc config KEY = VALUE... --> needs a few things specified:
  - Is the directive itself preserved in the output (like the <!-- caseproc ...
  --> markers), or consumed/stripped?
  - Does it take effect immediately (affecting selectors later in the same
  pass), or after the current region?
  - What happens on --validate? Is a config directive in a document applied when
   cross-checking?

  6. package * loop and marked regions

  The plan explains that package * loops through packages setting current ID
  each time. This means a single <!-- caseproc package * --> region generates
  all packages with their package_selections inline. This is powerful but worth
  stating explicitly in the plan, because it's a significant behavioral
  difference from how * currently works (just generates diagrams/lists, no
  heading nesting).

  7. Fate of existing format-specific selectors

  The plan adds sacm, gsn, ltac as format-detecting aliases, but doesn't say
  what happens to sacm/mermaid, gsn/mermaid, ltac/markdown, ltac/html. The
  Discussion section asks about this. My suggestion: keep the explicit variants
  (they're useful in mixed documents or when you want to force a format),
  deprecate or remove statement, references, info since they're superseded by
  element_selections.

  8. "Option to add missing elements to documents" is a stub

  Lines 224–227 are too vague to be actionable. "Add markers to LTAC" — what
  kind of markers? "Identify leaf nodes" — to do what with them? Either flesh
  this out or move it to a separate plan doc.

